/60023955"/><affiliation id="102047347" href="https://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/102047347"/></author></dc:creator><dc:description><abstract xmlns="" original="y" xml:lang="eng"><ce:para>One of the most important problems in the design of networks is the choice of a good topology i.e. interconnection pattern. Many topologies have been proposed in the past. Among those the ring topology has been used frequently because of its simplicity, expandability and regularity Unfortunately, the ring topology suffers from poor reliability and has large diameter. One can remedy these inconveniences by adding links to the ring. Usually, this is done in some systematic way and results in additional ring structures (i.e.. circuits). Networks with at least one ring structure are usually referred to as loop networks. In particular, circulant and 2-jump circulant have recently gained popularity due to their simplicity, expandability, and regularity. Compared with the simple ring network, they have improved diameter and reliability. In this paper, we solve the problem of 2-terminal (i.e.. poit-to-point) routing in 2-jump circulant network. In particular. we design a routing algorithm that, given arbitrary pair of processors, routes a message packet along the shortest path between the two processors. If l is the length of this path, and d is the diameter of the network, then the algorithm requires (∼) (d) preprocessing time and l = O(d) routing steps.</ce:para></abstract></dc:description><link href="https://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/0030706602" rel="self"/><link href="https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=0030706602&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus"/><link href="https://www.scopus.com/inward/citedby.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=0030706602&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus-citedby"/></coredata><affiliation id="60031106" href="https://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60031106"><affilname>University of